<p>In the first nine months of this year worldwide revenues from investment banking were $44.9 billion, 19% down on the same period last year, according to Dealogic, a financial-data provider. American clients accounted for almost half of the total. Revenues from mergers and acquisitions dropped by 18%, to $12.6 billion, yet they were still the most lucrative product. Equity-market earnings fell by 29%. Earnings from the debt markets accounted for a third of all revenues. Canadaâ€™s RBC was the only bank to grow its turnover compared with the first nine months of 2011: its revenues in the latest quarter jumped 44% from the same quarter last year, more than those of any other investment bank.</p>

